2. OCP: 3 - The MachineWorker class is not open for extension because it has a hard-coded list of machines and their capabilities. A more flexible design would allow adding new machine types without modifying the existing code.
3. LSP: 4 - The MachineWorker class violates the Liskov Substitution Principle because it requires specific subclasses to implement certain methods (e.g., washDishes, vacuumFloor). This can lead to runtime errors if a subclass does not implement these methods.
4. ISP: 5 - The MachineWorker class violates the Interface Segregation Principle because it has a single interface with many unrelated methods (washDishes, vacuumFloor, adjustTemperature, playMusic, securityScan, updateSoftware, generateReports). This can lead to unnecessary dependencies and complexity.
